Because I cannot find a benchmark tool for testing the settings of my network adapter, I test my configuration using a speed test. The speed test tells me the velocity of my upload and download speeds, and latency. Lower latency equals better performance. Different TCP/Network optimization programs have similar registry settings that someone can tweak to optimize their network. My strategy for optimizing a network adapter for multi-player gaming is to have constant performance without traffic control. I believe that in the past, a network card was a "phone jack," only an Ethernet port, without a processor. Older computers used the CPU to process packets. CPUs are probably faster than a processor(s) on a Network Interface Card (NIC). Offloading gaming packets to a NIC probably creates more heat, or reduces performance. I believe that gaming packets do not use checksums. People should use a speed test to choose their packet sizes. The fastest configuration may not be obvious. Configuring a NIC is a rational process, not a "common sense" process. (edited)

VidaPerron 2/20/2024 9:23 AM
The connections of a graphics card have maximum bandwidths or velocities. When people shop for a monitor, they should know if the connections of a monitor are the same as the connections on a graphics card. If the connection on a graphics card is greater than the connection on a monitor, the computer can crash. The voltages from incompatible connections, for example, from a high bandwidth connection to a lower bandwidth connection, probably create enough heat to shutdown the computer. A monitor might have an exciting maximum refresh rate for HDMI, but not Display Port. I had a graphics card with DP 1.4 and a monitor with DP 1.2. To be stable, I had to game in SD. If I used an HDMI cable, I had the ability to game in HD because the HDMI connections on the graphics card and the monitor were the same and they were faster (they had greater bandwidths than the Display Ports). This topic is critical when people have older things and when they want to reproduce 4K video. 3DMark has a GPU Bandwidth benchmark. If the score is low: 1) search for a BIOS setting (for changing the MHz of something different than the processor or memory), 2) use a different monitor to know if the bandwidth is different (because the performance of monitors is different). (edited)

VidaPerron 6/5/2024 12:49 PM
There are keyboards with removable keys called switches. After watching some videos and pretending to shop for hot-swappable mechanical keyboards, I discovered that these keyboards can be expensive. A high-quality barebones keyboard, keys, switches, and some mods are not cheap. Looking at these things did teach me how to shop for a keyboard. There are three popular types of switches, tactile, clicky, and linear. I want switches with the lowest latency (the fastest switches). A fast switch is not tactile, or clicky, and the distance for pressing or actuating the button is short. Knowing these things, I was able to find less expensive gaming keyboards with linear switches and RGB. I was also excited by watching videos on how to clean keyboards. Someday, I am going to remove the keycaps from my keyboard and wash them with soap and water. For someone that still wants to get a hot-swappable keyboard, save money by shopping for any keyboard with hot-swappable switches and only replace the switches that people use for gaming. (edited)

A procedure for overclocking memory to eliminate latency problems with a keyboard: 1) use the default XMP settings for memory, 2) reduce the speed of the memory, for example, from 4000 MHz to 3800 MHz, 3) increase the infinity fabric speed, 4) reduce the timings, for example, from 18, 46, 46, 48 to 18, 44, 44, 46 until the BIOS will no longer start (for the memory that I currently have in my machine, since I believe that when the first number is 16, a video game can crash, I do not want this number to be less than 18), 5) do not change any other timings; use the XMP or BIOS' automatic settings for the other timings. Also, use an AI program to make web searches for BIOS settings, for example, to configure the OS to operate the CPU, or to remove chipselect interleaving. After last night, I have used enough Watts to turn off the lights. When I returned to the game, I looked at my metrics. The fiery scene in Horizon Forbidden West at a cauldron was running the CPU with ~450W, and the GPU with ~320W. Because I hate crashing, I quit the game. I knew that I had to adjust the VddcrVddfull_Scale_Current setting. This setting controls how many Watts the CPU can have. Because I like the experience of being near a CPU utilizing a high amount of Watts, my VddcrVddfull_Scale_Current was at 1000. To continue playing the game, I had to change the setting to 600. Since I am now able to create my own power plan with powercfg.exe, I can still have the experience I like because I can disable the CPU idle setting. This makes the CPU run at 100% without a load. For gaming, the experience of the computer never throttling or idling is more instantaneous action! I believe that I might like these new settings more. Another strategy for overclocking memory - When not using XMP, Carefully press the on/off button for 5+ seconds when the computer fails at startup. It might take several attempts to shutdown and startup the machine before the BIOS has the default settings. If there is an LED panel on the motherboard, observe the instruction before the BIOS starts with the default settings to know when the motherboard will successfully restart after failing. 1) change the "fail count" setting in the BIOS to 1 2) choose a DRAM-Frequency 3) look at the timings (tCL-tRCD-tRP-tRAS) or (tCL-tRCD[RD], tRCD[WR]-tRP-tRAS) where tRCD[RD] = tRCD[WR] -> 18, 24, 24, 42 or 18, 24, 24, 24, 42 because tRCD[RD] = tRCD[WR] 4) enter the CL number, and lower the tRAS number 1 or 2 units, and then successively change the tRCD and tRP timings until the discovery of the fastest timings that allow the machine to start -> 18, 24, 24, 24, 42 -> 18, 24, 24, 24, 40 -> 18, 23, 23, 23, 40 -> 18, 22, 22, 22, 40 Make certain that the XMP setting/profile says AUTO. Do not adjust the secondary timings. 4) Lower the ProcODT, which might cause the computer to fail when starting Use Ryzen Master, or other software to observe the other default settings. Look at the DRAM Calculator for Ryzen to know other settings for adjusting the motherboard's memory. Once the settings are finished, if the computer will not start without restarting, consider lowering the DRAM-Frequency. (edited)

The image in this post activates the Power Saving system in the OPNSense (UNIX) firewall. ACPI is a system in the BIOS and operating system for using information about hardware to control the operating system and CPU. The default settings for Windows 10 and 11 make the CPU operate autonomously. Without disabling this setting, the operating system will not use ACPI information to enhance the operation of the CPU. The BIOS settings for ACPI on an ASRock motherboard are: PSS Support, sleep/hibernation states, CPPC, CPPC preferred cores (and more general power saving settings are to make CPU cores sleep by enabling C-States). If this is too complex, use 10-12 fans in a large case to cool a computer, and use different Power Saving profiles provided by Windows. Use the Power Saver when watching movies or YouTube videos, or High/Ultimate performance when playing video games. Power Saving removes heat from a room where there is a computer. Copilot: "If I were a female, I would scent my closet with an oregano sachet." Me: What is the subjunctive tense in English? Copilot: The subjunctive tense in English is used to express wishes, hypothetical situations, demands, or suggestions. It's often found in clauses that start with "if," "wish," "as if," or "although." For example: Wish: "I wish I were taller." Hypothetical: "If he were here, he would help." Demand: "She insists that he come to the meeting." Suggestion: "It is important that she be informed." It's a bit of a quirky tense in English, adding some flair to those imaginative and wishful thoughts. Me: Why does the subjunctive use the verb "to be" conjugated for the plural pronoun they? Copilot (answer 1): The subjunctive mood often uses "were" instead of "was" for all subjects to indicate hypothetical or non-real situations. This usage comes from older forms of English and helps distinguish between statements of fact and statements of wish or possibility. So, "If I were a bird" signals a hypothetical situation, rather than "If I was a bird," which sounds more like a factual statement about the past. Fascinating, right? What else are you curious about? Copilot (answer 2): The subjunctive mood uses "were" for all subjects, including singular ones like "I" or "he," as well as plural ones like "they," to indicate hypothetical, wishful, or non-real situations. This consistent use across different subjects is what sets the subjunctive apart from the indicative mood, where verbs change based on the subject.
